			<title>Metal Gear Solid V: Ground Zeroes</title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?76598-Metal-Gear-Solid-V-Ground-Zeroes&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Thu, 20 Mar 2014 23:08:09 GMT</pubDate>
			<description><![CDATA[So, I knew what I was getting into with this, and had decided it could wait, but my curiosity got the best of me and I ended up buying the PS3 digital version on it's midnight launch. I am posting this here instead of in the monthly release thread to serve as a bit of a PSA for anyone who also got...]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>So, I knew what I was getting into with this, and had decided it could wait, but my curiosity got the best of me and I ended up buying the PS3 digital version on it's midnight launch. I am posting this here instead of in the monthly release thread to serve as a bit of a PSA for anyone who also got bit with the same curiosity bug.<br />
<br />
I find it difficult to place this game. If you read any other gaming forums you might already have some preconceptions on what this is. And I'm going to be honest, the criticisms are more valid than I thought they would be. Most of what you have heard is probably correct. It really sort of is a demo, but it's also much better than almost any demo you will ever play. I don't think it's unfair that they are charging for it, although I do think they are charging too much. Particularly for the PS4/Xone versions. ($20 on PS3/360, $30 for PS4/Xone). <br />
<br />
There is one campaign mission that will take you about two hours to complete. It is not a long mission, but you will spend a lot of that time learning how to play the game, exploring your options, and restarting from a checkpoint if you are trying to play it stealthily. Future playthroughs can probably be done in 30 minutes. There are also 4-5 bonus missions on the same map that also take about 30 minutes. The purpose of these missions is to demonstrate different ways of playing the game. So for example, whether a mission takes place at night or at day makes a big difference. The map is not a large open world, but instead one single large base that lets you approach your objective however you want. It's an impressive step forward for the series, but nothing you haven't seen from other games. <br />
<br />
<br />
The gameplay is very good. While some of the mainline MGS fans complain about certain aspects, I personally think it feels exactly like the successor to Peacewalker should. It controls well, and never really frustrated me. You can mark enemies with your binoculars. If you arouse suspicion, you will get a small light indicator pointing in their direction and the music will get tense. If you get spotted, you will enter slow motion to give you a chance to take them out before they call for help. The latter can be turned off, as purists hate it, but I think with the bigger maps it's kind of necessary. You are generally more exposed than you have been in any other game, and it can be hard to take every angle of sight into account.<br />
<br />
Story wise the game is very unsatisfying. You won't see much more than you saw in the trailers for the game, and the way it is put together doesn't really do anything to make you excited for the Phantom Pain. There are a few moments of intrigue that should fuel speculation, but it isn't the big lead in into the next game that I hoped it would be. Nor does it stand on it's own very well. And while I haven't gotten or listened to them yet, the collectible audio logs are very dark and very depressing. The game is as much about Guantanamo Bay as it is about the fictional antagonists and their conspiracy plots. I figure Kojima is trying to provide a reason for Big Boss to become a villain by introducing him to horror and pain that can't be ignored, but some of this stuff is really f-ed up. Do not want. <br />
<br />
<br />
I'm willing to ignore the fact that they are probably selling this to pay for the development of the rest of the game and be grateful I was giving the chance to play it this early, but if I had to say whether or not someone else should buy it or wait, I would say wait. This feels like something that will be (or should be?) distributed alongside the main game, either as a pre-order promotion, or simply as the prologue of the game. If the gameplay wasn't so smooth I would say it felt like a prototype version, sort of like the opening chapter to Tomb Raider.<br />
<br />
If you preordered the PS3 version, they gave you the PS3 version of Peacewalker with it for free. This is a pretty great deal, and I find it a bit surprising the cheapest version is the one that got offered such a good deal. All you really get for paying $10 extra with the PS4 version is better graphics and a better frame rate. I sort of think the people who bought the PS3/Xone versions probably deserve a discount for the main game when it is released. <br />
<br />
There is also a mobile companion app, which I wasn't able to use because of connection problems with my PS3. It's basically one of those &quot;second screen&quot; apps that got hyped up so much at the last E3. You can view the game map, listing to audio logs, or play some kind of base building minigame which sounds a lot like a feature from Peacewalker.</div>

]]></content:encoded>
