			<title>The One Game that Needs an 8-bit Retrofit</title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?76583-The-One-Game-that-Needs-an-8-bit-Retrofit&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Mon, 17 Mar 2014 02:54:39 GMT</pubDate>
			<description><![CDATA[I just learned about Mega Man 9 the other day (I know, I'm like 6 years out of date).  It's a fantastic idea.  The concept (for other hermits like me) is basically: recreate an 8-bit era game with all the same basic mechanics as Mega Man 2, except with new, creative, challenges.  From all I've read...]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>I just learned about Mega Man 9 the other day (I know, I'm like 6 years out of date).  It's a fantastic idea.  The concept (for other hermits like me) is basically: recreate an 8-bit era game with all the same basic mechanics as Mega Man 2, except with new, creative, challenges.  From all I've read of reviews, the developers absolutely nailed it.  It makes perfect sense to me.  I played Mega Man games up through the SNES era, and while they were still fun and superior in many ways, the basic formula was just too restrictive to keep up with the competition, and Mega Man in the late 90s.  Nostalgia is obviously the big draw, but it's not impossible that even after six 8-bit installments, there's still new content to enjoy.  <br />
<br />
I'm not sure that would work with many other NES games.  I think most NES games are best left in the 80s, (Capcom wasn't even able to pull it off twice for Mega Man).  There are enough indie developers capable putting an innovative twist on side-scrollers that we certainly don't need to bring back Contra or TMNT1, or even, I'd argue: Metroid, though I'm sure others might disagree on that one.  Certainly there seems to be little point in trying to re-create the 8-bit jRPG experience.  New levels for the original Super Mario Bros 1 could be interesting, but most likely anyone who would play that are already playing hacked ROMs.  In general I think if you're going to mine the 80s for videogame ideas, you'll be best off adapting them to a modern style.  But there's one NES game that is truly unique.  One that's never been surpassed, probably <i>cannot</i> be surpassed with modern gameplay expectations, and that I think people WOULD play if the style and presentation was recreated accurately enough and the content was superlative.<br />
<br />
Obviously, that game is: <b>The Legend of Zelda</b>.  I mean the original, the one with the shiny gold cartridge.  It's the one with the grid-based overworld map, the room-based labyrinths, the economy of tiles, the spare feeling that Link is alone in his quest with maybe only a little help from cryptic characters with dialogue measured in the 10s of characters; the raw challenge of the enemy rooms, the devious puzzles, the paucity of in-game hints.  I think it could be phenomenal: a game with (nearly) strict NES-style mechanics adhering to the era's conventions, but with new traps, new puzzles, new enemies, new items, and new twists on old ideas.</div>

]]></content:encoded>
