			<title>Titanfall</title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?76570-Titanfall&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Fri, 14 Mar 2014 01:37:27 GMT</pubDate>
			<description><![CDATA[Bear with me, because before we talk about Titanfall, we're talking about Call of Duty and Battlefield.  It's the game that this will be compared with the most, and it's important to consider what both of those games bring to the table before we can get into any discussion of Titanfall. 
 
I'm a...]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>Bear with me, because before we talk about Titanfall, we're talking about Call of Duty and Battlefield.  It's the game that this will be compared with the most, and it's important to consider what both of those games bring to the table before we can get into any discussion of Titanfall.<br />
<br />
I'm a big fan of shooters.  The Call of Duty series in particular has always been a favorite, but probably not for reasons a lot of people consider.  I enjoy it because I can get home, sit down, play for 10 minutes and log out, make myself some dinner, come back watch some TV, play Titanfall for a few more minutes, and then do something else.  If you sit down for most games, you have to sit down, uninterrupted for at least 30 minutes. But I love it because the engine is so seamless.<br />
<br />
<b>On Engines and Netcode</b><br />
<br />
The only game with an equally smooth engine up until now has been Halo, and other than Reach, I've never been a big fan of the Halo games (just an actual gameplay problem, but I fucking love the matchmaking and engine itself).  <br />
<br />
All games have delays caused by the following:<br />
Your reaction time<br />
Latency<br />
Video Delay<br />
<br />
However, other games introduce a lot of additional delays: in Battlefield, if someone shoots you with 1 bullet, the server won't send that bullet to you until either a certain period of time has passed, or it has enough data in a packet to send to you.  So what you'll see is that you instantly die, because it sent 2-3 bullets at once.  To get around this a bit, they limit how fast bullets can hit you, but if you have 2 people shooting at you...  Then there is some nonsensical registration delay in Battlefield.  If I shoot you, my screen will show you get hit, but your screen will show you get hit up to 140ms(+network delay) later.  The fucked up part about this is that hackers (not cheaters) have checked the memory space, and noted that your system actually knows it was hit immediately.  But it doesn't show you get hit until after the delay.<br />
<br />
Halo and early Call of Duty games never really had those problems.  Their updates usually happen as fast as latency allows.  It means when you play, you generally have a pretty fair estimation of whats happening on the screen as fast as possible.  Since the original team left to join Respawn (Titanfall), the netcode has had a large number of problems.  Testing seems to show that they don't understand how latency works.  The original COD games used an engine that gave &quot;host advantage.&quot;  It meant the lower your latency, the more of an advantage you had against anyone else.  After the team split, they started trying to do more and more punishment systems to reduce the Host Advantage, but they're idiots. Testing shows that they punished based on ping, rather than 1-way traffic.  Halo and Battlefield take care of this by just allowing you to kill each other.  That works great in Halo, but in BF,due to the previously mentioned problems and bullet travel time, it means you constantly kill each other.  Which can be significantly more punishing than a 10-20ms advantage.<br />
<br />
Source Engine games are pretty wonky.  They have a lot of look advantage issues, which is generally only a problem in Counter-Strike (where 1 shot from most weapons can kill you).  But in general their netcode is just &quot;okay.&quot;  It's better than Battlefield, but not as good as Halo or the early CoD games.<br />
<br />
It's too early to tell for sure, because weapon balance in games can do a lot to counter these problems, but the Titanfall seems to blow CoD out of the water, and performs roughly equal to Halo.  The engine runs the Source Engine, but they use custom netcode.  And then it uses dedicated servers, which removes the Host Advantage problem.<br />
<br />
<b>Gameplay Mechanics</b><br />
<br />
Now, there are lots of things I don't like about the Call of Duty series: I hate instant knifes that kill you even while you're busy shooting someone in the face, I hate the way the lobby system works (or doesn't).  Titanfall doesn't fix either of those things.  Sure, you kick people instead of knifing them, but it's really the same thing.  I wish I could say that they implemented Halos Lobby system, and made bullets slow down the kick or something, but I can't.  This is one of my few complaints about the game.  In Battlefield, I hate how wonky knifing someone can be.  If you're on different objects with slightly different elevation, often the knife won't work.  Titanfall has two modes: Jump Kick, and Execution.  Execution is basically the Battlefield &quot;I snuck up behind you, so now you're dead&quot; option, but it works more seamlessly. If your positioning is weird, your character leans at the waist or whatever needs to happen to complete the animation.  Jump Kick is more for &quot;I'm charging at you and am out of bullets, so here's a boot to the face&quot;  It makes sense, but it's the one situation where they can have a severe latency advantage.  Due to Jump Kick, and their netcode, it gives the attacker a small edge.  <br />
<br />
But I don't consider this a problem.  Titanfall is all about fast movement. It's the game we all wanted Brink to be, but wasn't.  It's a game about fast movement.  The better you are at the game, the more likely you're chaining together wall runs, and getting faster.  There are areas where a normal double jump will have you hanging on the edge of a 2nd floor window sill to get in, but if you wall run up to the point where you would make that jump you're moving so much faster that you can double jump <i>into</i> the 3rd floor window.  This means that the more skilled you are, the more mobile you are.  This makes gun battles awesome.  You will find yourself tracking people bouncing off of walls, trying to hit them before they get away, or you'll be flying through the air and suddenly get hit. Since you're moving so fast, you likely don't have a chance to locate the shooter, and you just alter your trajectory, trying to get to safety before you try running into them.<br />
<br />
This makes snipers an interesting class to play.  Sniping is completely possible, although more doable on some game-types than others.  And quick scoping is a skill maneuver.  They haven't done any ridiculous targeting mechanics, if you're sniping, the shots are completely reliant on skill.  In COD, if you were sniping, you could &quot;quick scope&quot; and it would auto-target snap to a nearby target for you.  This could allow people to shoot you at 90 degree angles to where they were facing (drag scoping).  Using the scope in Titanfall doesn't provide any auto-targetting.  That makes it difficult to hit a target sometimes, but it didn't feel outrageous.  And you don't have to worry about any bullshit like the newer Call of Duty games were you scope in, and the bullet doesn't go where you're aiming for 250+ms (I'd be fine if it went close to where you're aiming, but when you miss someone 10 feet away when their entire body fills the scope, it's crazy).<br />
<br />
I'm not good enough with sniping to judge the quality of sniping in this game.  I'll update next week after my brother gets home and has some time to test it (his reaction times have been tested to be in the top 0.2%, which would put him in the top 5% for fighter pilots, so his sniping is usually crazy).<br />
<br />
<b>Campaign</b><br />
<br />
What? Campaign? I thought this game was multi-player only!<br />
<br />
It is.  This is the weakest part of the game.  It's a unique idea, and very interesting, but there is an immediate problem.<br />
<br />
So there are 15 levels in the game, and the Campaign has each level introduced with a cut scene explaining why you're there, and what your objective is.  6v6 maps, where it preferentially places players who have played the level as IMC completely onto the Militia team.  Since the game has been out awhile, this probably isn't a big deal to find people playing, but once it's been out for longer, it might be difficult to finish the campaign.  You need to play the Campaign to unlock the other Titans (Ogre and Stryder).  There is no real bonus for winning or losing any of the maps, BUT, since you play through the IMC first, then play through as the Militia, the Militia tend to have significantly more experienced players.  This means you play though the entire campaign, and likely lose 15 matches in a row.  Several games I played as IMC would be me and 5 players with single digit levels.  On normal games, I'm about 3:2 win ratio.  As IMC, I was 1:15.  Not a great way to start the game, so I suggest jumping straight into Classic and waiting until you have a friend to do campaign with.<br />
<br />
<b>Multiplayer &amp; NPC's</b><br />
<br />
I see a lot of complaints about NPC's from people that either haven't played, or are playing it like it's CoD.  The latter players are pretty easy to spot, because they're trying to camp, or stalking around with ADS up.<br />
<br />
You play a Pilot.  You have cybernetic implants, and bad ass armor.  You can take 3x as much damage as the normal NPC's.  You have a few possible upgrades, such as a Cloak (like Predator) or <br />
<br />
There are multiple NPC's in the game: Grunts, Spectres, and Auto-Titans.  If you're not in your Titan while deployed, it will behave as an NPC, and either guard its current area or follow you around (you can switch its orders).  Spectres are interesting, they do more damage than Grunts, bur there are fewer of them.  And you can run up on enemy spectres, and hack them.  Hacked Spectres have an AI upgrade, and will follow you around, watching your back.  Having an NPC watch doors for you is awesome.  <br />
<br />
None of the NPC's in the game can see Cloaked Pilots, but if they take a bullet, their cloak will flicker, and I've been kicked to death by a Grunt once while in combat with an enemy pilot and cloaked.  Death from NPC's is embarrassing.<br />
<br />
The best part of the NPC's is that most of your weapon upgrades happen from PC-&gt;NPC interaction.  Need a new scope?  Kill 100 Grunts.  That's way easier than trying to progress in strictly PvP games.  Some of the challenges required in CoD games would drive me insane.  You'd get into game after game against a team, and not be able to make progress on your challenges.<br />
<br />
Titanfall makes everyone feel like a bad ass.  After the round finishes, the game transitions to a 1 life remaining for all players, and an evac ship marker shows up on the map.  If the losing team can get to that point and evacuate, those who survive get a lot of extra points (300-600), but even if you don't make it, in the rush for their team to stop the evacuation, you can often take out an enemy titan, jumping on top and filling the computer full of bullets (this is called rodeoing in the game).  This means that largely in this game, even losing can remain fun.  <br />
<br />
<b>So... Many... Words...</b><br />
<br />
This game is fun. If you like Action-based FPS games, you'll love this.  If you just feel like you're terrible at FPS games, and that feeling prevents you from playing, you should still give it a try.  I haven't enjoyed a FPS this much since the COD4:Modern Warfare.</div>

]]></content:encoded>
